anks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sung, Jung, Yong, Chang, Kwang, Sang, Dong, Hyun, Jae, Jin, Kyung, Jong, Chong, Chung, Byung, Jeong, Pyong, Myong, Hak, Jin Hwan, Sook, Yeong, Choon.","Korean: variant of   O  .","Japanese: variant of <b>Ō</b> (see   O  )."],"variants":[{"name":"O","meanings":["(1997: 122;2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Bo Young, Chae, Chong Hwan, Dong Kun, Ho, Hwan, Hyun, Jong, Jung, Ki Soon, Kwang.  Korean Min, Chong, Chol, Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."]}]},{"name":"Lavagna","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Carmine, Attilio, Carlo, Cataldo, Enrico, Gaetano, Gennaro, Rocco, Sal.  Spanish Alfonso, Glicerio, Liborio.","Italian: ethnic name for a member of the Alemanni, an ancient Germanic people inhabiting what is now southern Germany, from a shortened form of <b>Alamagna</b> ‘Alemannia’, i.e. ‘land of the Alemanni’. Compare   Lamanna  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lamanna","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Rocco, Carlo, Carmine, Vito, Luigi, Pasquale, Sal, Amedeo, Anella, Angelo, Carmelo.","Italian (southern):","(also <b>La Manna</b>): topographic name from <i>manna</i>, a term denoting a type of ash tree, + the definite article <i>la</i>."]}]},{"name":"Ruffinus","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of A